  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Bapl Building AFG Peace Locally</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Building Afghan Peace Locally programme is a multi- partner programme combining different approaches on the basis of ongoing programming funded by Oxfam Novib into one integrated programme implemented by six partner organisations; ADA, AWSDC, CHA, CoAR, CPAU/PTRO, and SMO. The programme has been developed in order to submit to a EC call which was granted. The total amount of the programme(&#x80; 958,539) will be covered by EC and the remaining by Oxfam Novib. Oxfam Novib will coordinate the project from the Country Officein Kabul.

Objective: to strengthen civil society capacities in  4 Afghan provinces in effectively resolving and mitigating conflict whilst enhancing the status and inclusion of women and opening a national debate on peace and conflict resolution.

Envisaged results are
1. In 8 districts across 4 provinces, local civil society and governance actors have established effective and socially inclusive peacebuilding structures. This service will be in reach for aprox. 835,000 people living in the districts.

2. In target districts, the role of women in local peace and conflict issues has been systematically addressed and gender equality has been improved

3  . Research and documentation of models has promoted best practice in linking state and non-state actors in peacebuilding, illustrating how women can play an active role in civil society and particularly in peacebuilding

4. Lobbying based on practical experience, research and popular mobilisation has helped bring about changes in policy and practice of the Afghan authorities:


Spin offs:
-       Currently the Afghan government&#x92;s main focus is on the reconciliation process with little recognition of the role local conflict play in the national conflict. This programme with its strong advocacy and campaigning component will be able to inform and disseminate divers programme experiences to both afghan government and public, which can lead to the Afghan government recognizing the need for local peace building and enforcing a national strategy.
-       The programme will strengthen local mechanisms for conflicttransformation ensuring inclusion of women (both as victims as actors) and minorities. These groups in the past have often been negatively affected by local level conflict resolution mechanisms. Especially girls and women are used to reconcile between households in conflict. Further, the recognition within communities as well as at government level the specific circumstances women were and are affected by conflict isan important milestone to further integrate women in conflict resolution and peace building efforts.</narrative>
  </description>
